# Coerce to numeric, turning non-numeric strings into NaN
df['age'] = pd.to_numeric(df['age'], errors='coerce')
# Remove rows where age is NaN or is an outlier
df.dropna(subset=['age'], inplace=True)
df = df[df['age'] <= 100]
df['age'] = df['age'].astype(int)
# Clean 'education' and 'gender' columns for placeholder values
df['education'] = df['education'].replace('select one', np.nan)
df['gender'] = df['gender'].replace('select one', np.nan)
# It's impossible to be a Wharton listener without being a Sirius listener.
inconsistent_responses = df[(df['sirius'] == 'No') & (df['wharton'] == 'Yes')]
print(f"Found {len(inconsistent_responses)} inconsistent responses. Removing them.")
df = df.drop(inconsistent_responses.index)
df.replace('', np.nan, inplace=True)

print("\nShape of the data after cleaning:", df.shape)

2.1 ii) Our initial dataset contained 1764 responses. After cleaning, we were left with 1757 valid responses. Here are our cleaning process and their explanations:

  1. Age Cleaning: We noticed that there are some non-numeric and outlier values in the 'age' column. Thus we converted the column to a numeric type, forcing invalid entries into NaN. We also removed rows with these invalid ages, as well as any clear outliers that don't make sense, such as the age > 100.
  2. Logical Inconsistencies: We noticed that there are two respondents who claims to listen to Wharton Radio but not to Sirius Radio. Since Wharton Business Radio is a channel on SiriusXM, it doesn't make since that users claimed to listen to Wharton Radio but not to Sirius Radio, thus we have removed these rows.
  3. Other missing values: We identified blank strings and placeholder values such as "select one" across the dataset and converted them to NaN to represent them as missing. We also decided to keep rows with missing demographic data, as they still contain valuable listenership information.

2.1 iii) From the summary statistics and visualizations, we can observe the following about the survey respondents:

  • Age: The respondents are relatively young. From the bell curve, most data is concentrated at a mean age of about 30 and a median of 28. It's also interesting that the distribution is skewed towards younger individuals. Gender: The sample is predominantly male (1007 respondents) compared to female (744 respondents).
  • Education: A large portion of the respondents have "Some college, no diploma; or Associates degree" (743) followed by those with a "Bachelors degree" (614). From this we can tell that the sample of this experiment are mostly students/educated people with prior knowledge and understanding of the experiment.
  • Income: The most common income bracket is "$30,000 - $50,000". A significant number of respondents have an annual household income below $50,000, which is a reasonable range for students and people who have justed graduated and entered the workforce.
  • Listenership: A vast majority of respondents reported listening to Sirius Radio. However, only a small fraction of those listen to the Wharton Business Radio.

This demographic profile suggests that the MTurk workers who took this survey are likely younger individuals, possibly students or those early in their careers, who are looking to supplement their income.

2.2 Sample properties

2.2 i) We compared our data and its demographics to that of the U.S. population in 2014(not current because thats when the experiment was implemented) to determine if our sample is representiive.

  • Age: The median age in the U.S. in 2014 was approximately 37.6 years. Our sample has a median age of 28, which is significantly younger.

    • Source: United States Census Bureau, "Annual Estimates of the Resident Population for Selected Age Groups by Sex for the United States, States, Counties, and Puerto Rico Commonwealth and Municipios: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2014." https://www.census.gov/data/tables/2014/demo/popest/nation-detail.html

  • Gender: The U.S. population in 2014 was approximately 50.8% female. Our sample is about 42% female (744 out of 1751 non-missing gender entries), meaning it is skewed towards males.

    • Source: United States Census Bureau, "Annual Estimates of the Resident Population by Sex, Race, and Hispanic Origin for the United States, States, and Counties: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2014." https://www.census.gov/data/tables/2014/demo/popest/nation-detail.html

  • Education: In 2014, about 32% of the U.S. population aged 25 and over had a bachelor's degree or higher. In our sample (excluding those under 25 for a rough comparison), the proportion is much higher.

    • Source: United States Census Bureau, "Educational Attainment in the United States: 2014." https://www.census.gov/data/tables/2014/demo/education-attainment/cps-detailed-tables.html

  • Income: The median household income in the U.S. in 2014 was around $53,700. Our sample's income distribution is skewed towards lower brackets due to the majority of our expriemnt subjects are young and students.

    • Source: United States Census Bureau, "Income and Poverty in the United States: 2014." https://www.census.gov/library/publications/2015/demo/p60-252.html

Based on these observations and outside sources, and comparing to our data distribution, NO, this sample does not appear to be a random sample from the general U.S. population. It is younger, more male, more educated, and has a lower household income on average.

2.2 ii)
Research on MTurk demographics from around 2014 indicates that the MTurk population itself is not representative of the U.S. population. Studies conducted around 2014 consistently found that MTurk workers are younger, more educated, and have lower incomes than the general U.S. population.

  • Source: Paolacci, G., Chandler, J., & Ipeirotis, P. G. (2010). "Running experiments on Amazon Mechanical Turk." Judgment and Decision Making, 5(5), 411-419.
  • Source: Berinsky, A. J., Huber, G. A., & Lenz, G. S. (2012). "Evaluating online labor markets for experimental research: Amazon.com's Mechanical Turk." Political Analysis, 20(3), 351-368.

Our sample's demographics align well with these known characteristics of the MTurk population. For instance, one study from that era found that MTurk workers were more likely to be female, while our sample is majority male, so there might be some sampling bias even within the MTurk population, also others have found a more even split or a male majority, suggesting that gender distribution can vary depending on the specific task and time of the survey. However, the age and income distributions are quite consistent with typical MTurk worker profiles.

  • Source: Ross, J., Irani, L., Silberman, M. S., Zaldivar, A., & Tomlinson, B. (2010). "Who are the crowdworkers?: shifting demographics in mechanical turk." CHI'10 extended abstracts on human factors in computing systems, 2863-2872.

So we came into the conclusion that even though its not the perfect fit, the sample is more representative of the MTurk populiation based on academic research on the demographics of Amazon Mechanical Turk Workers.

2.3 Executive Summary

  1. Goal of the Study: The primary goal of this study was to estimate the total audience size for the "Business Radio Powered by the Wharton School" show on SiriusXM as of May 2014.

  2. Method: A survey was conducted on Amazon Mechanical Turk (MTurk), gathering 1757 valid responses from a U.S. based audience. We calculated the proportion of respondents who listen to Wharton Business Radio among those who listen to SiriusXM. This proportion was then multiplied by the total number of SiriusXM subscribers in January 2014 (51.6 million) to estimate the total audience size.

  3. Findings: Within our sample, we found that approximately 5.01% of SiriusXM listeners also listen to the Wharton Business Radio channel. Based on this proportion, we estimate the total audience for the Wharton show to be approximately 2,583,799 listeners.

  4. Limitations: The main limitation of this study is the reliance on a sample from MTurk. As established, this sample is not representative of the general U.S. population, and it may also not be representative of the SiriusXM subscriber base. The demographics of our sample (younger, more educated, lower income) may have different listening habits than the overall SiriusXM audience. Therefore, the actual audience size could be different from our estimate.

2.4 Proposal to Estimate Wharton Business Radio Audience Size

Method:

To get a more accurate and updated estimate of the audience size with a $1000 budget, we propose a multi-pronged approach:

  • Targeted Online Surveys: Instead of a general MTurk survey, we should use platforms that allow for more specific demographic targeting, such as Prolific or YouGov. We can set quotas to ensure our sample more closely matches the demographics of the general U.S. population or, ideally, known demographics of satellite radio listeners. The survey would again ask about listenership of SiriusXM and the Wharton channel. Also to ensure statistical precision, we will aim for at least 400 confirmed SiriusXM listeners in the survey sample, which allows estimates with a margin of error of roughly 3 percentage points.

  • Social Media Analytics: We can analyze social media data (e.g., from X/Twitter, Reddit) for mentions of "Wharton Business Radio" and related keywords. While this won't give a direct audience count, it can provide insights into the engagement and demographics of the online audience, which can be used to supplement survey findings.

summary = (df_2015.groupby(['Degree', 'Field', 'Sex'], as_index=False)['Number'].sum())
table = (summary.pivot_table(index=['Degree','Field'], columns='Sex', values='Number', fill_value=0).reset_index())
if {'Female','Male'}.issubset(table.columns):
    table['Total'] = table['Female'] + table['Male']
    table['Pct_Female'] = np.where(table['Total'] > 0, table['Female'] / table['Total'], np.nan)
else:
    for col in ['Female','Male']:
        if col not in table.columns:
            table[col] = 0
    table['Total'] = table['Female'] + table['Male']
    table['Pct_Female'] = np.where(table['Total'] > 0, table['Female'] / table['Total'], np.nan)
table = table.sort_values(['Degree','Field']).reset_index(drop=True)

4.1 EDA: Relationship between payroll changes and performance

Argument: performance in year t might be more related to change in payroll from t 1 to t than to level in t.

Create increment in payroll.

i) For year 2013, consider:

diff: payroll2013 payroll2012

log diff: log(payroll2013) log(payroll2012)

Explain why the log difference is more appropriate here.

The log difference is more appropriate because it decribes a percent change rather than an absolute change. For example, if a team spends 100mil one year and spends 200mil the next, then spending has doubled. However, if a team is spending 200mil and they spend 300mil the next year, then they only increased spending by 50%. The percent change is more likely to relate to changes in motivation than the absolute dollar difference ("according to expectancy theory and hedonistic adaptation").

However, the log difference approximating the percent change is more accurate for small percent changes (below 10% or so). The baseball dataset contains percent changes much higher; therefore, caution should be used in interpreting the results.

4.2 Exploratory questions

i) Which five teams had the highest increase in payroll between 2010 and 2014 (inclusive)?

ii) Between 2010 and 2014 (inclusive), which team(s) improved the most in percentage gains in wins?

Answer to 4.2 (i): Teams with Highest Payroll Increase

Depending on what method you use to measure payroll increases from 2010-2014, the top five teams change. Here I've given top 5 teams in terms of logarithimic payroll increase (not absolute) because that provides a better measure of proportional change.

Based on our analysis of log differences (which represent percent changes in payroll), the five teams with the largest percent increase in their payroll between 2010 and 2014 are:

  1. Los Angeles Dodgers in 2013 (82% increase)
  2. Miami Marlins in 2012 (73% increase)
  3. Houston Astros in 2014 (70% increase)
  4. Kansas City Royals in 2012 (52% increase)
  5. Texas Rangers in 2011 (51% increase)

This aligns with the data shown in our results table, which identified these teams as having the highest log differences in payroll. As explained earlier, using log differences provides a better measurement of proportional changes in team payrolls than absolute dollar differences, especially when comparing teams with different financial resources.

# Find largest year-to-year percent payroll increases within 2010-2014

# Use the loaded `data` DataFrame
data_10_14 = bb[bb['year'].between(2010, 2014)].copy()

# Sort and create lagged payroll and year
data_10_14 = data_10_14.sort_values(['team', 'year']).copy()
data_10_14['prev_payroll'] = data_10_14.groupby('team')['payroll'].shift(1)
data_10_14['prev_year'] = data_10_14.groupby('team')['year'].shift(1)

# I am keeping only data for consective years (this aligns with the sample solution provided)
data_10_14['is_consec'] = (data_10_14['year'] - data_10_14['prev_year'] == 1)
consec = data_10_14[data_10_14['is_consec'] & data_10_14['prev_payroll'].notna()].copy()

# Compute absolute change, percent change and log diff
consec['abs_change'] = consec['payroll'] - consec['prev_payroll']
consec['percent_change'] = (consec['payroll'] - consec['prev_payroll']) / consec['prev_payroll'] * 100
consec['log_diff'] = np.log(consec['payroll']) - np.log(consec['prev_payroll'])

# Top 5 by percent change
top5 = consec.sort_values('percent_change', ascending=False).head(5).copy()

# Round values for presentation
top5['percent_change_round'] = top5['percent_change'].round().astype(int)
top5['abs_change_round'] = top5['abs_change'].round(1)

show_tbl = top5[['team', 'year', 'log_diff', 'prev_payroll', 'payroll', 'abs_change', 'percent_change', ]].copy().round(3)

# Analyzing the largest year-to-year changes in payroll within the 2010-2014 window

# Use the already loaded and filtered data_10_14 from cell 12
data_2010_2014_sorted = data_10_14.sort_values(['team', 'year'])

# Create previous year columns
data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_year'] = data_2010_2014_sorted.groupby('team')['year'].shift(1)
data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_payroll'] = data_2010_2014_sorted.groupby('team')['payroll'].shift(1)

# Calculate year-to-year changes (only where we have consecutive years)
data_2010_2014_sorted['is_consecutive'] = (data_2010_2014_sorted['year'] - data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_year'] == 1)
data_2010_2014_sorted['payroll_change'] = data_2010_2014_sorted['payroll'] - data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_payroll']
data_2010_2014_sorted['log_diff'] = np.where(
    data_2010_2014_sorted['is_consecutive'],
    np.log(data_2010_2014_sorted['payroll']) - np.log(data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_payroll']),
    np.nan
)
data_2010_2014_sorted['percent_change'] = np.where(
    data_2010_2014_sorted['is_consecutive'],
    (data_2010_2014_sorted['payroll'] - data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_payroll']) / data_2010_2014_sorted['prev_payroll'] * 100,
    np.nan
)

# Get the top 5 year-to-year changes by log difference (percent change)
top_5_yearly_changes = data_2010_2014_sorted.dropna(subset=['log_diff']).sort_values('log_diff', ascending=False).head(5)

# Create a visualization of these top changes
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# For each team in top 5, show the payroll before and after the big change
teams = top_5_yearly_changes['team'].unique()
colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0, 1, len(teams)))

for i, team in enumerate(teams):
    team_data = top_5_yearly_changes[top_5_yearly_changes['team'] == team]
    for _, row in team_data.iterrows():
        years = [row['prev_year'], row['year']]
        payrolls = [row['prev_payroll'], row['payroll']]
        plt.plot(years, payrolls, 'o-', linewidth=2, markersize=8, label=f"{team} ({int(row['prev_year'])}-{int(row['year'])})", color=colors[i])
        
        # Add percentage increase annotation
        midpoint_x = np.mean(years)
        midpoint_y = np.mean(payrolls)
        plt.annotate(f"+{row['percent_change']:.1f}%", 
                    xy=(midpoint_x, midpoint_y),
                    xytext=(0, 10),
                    textcoords='offset points',
                    ha='center',
                    fontsize=9,
                    bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', fc='white', alpha=0.7))

plt.title('Top 5 Largest Year-to-Year Payroll Increases (2010-2014)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Payroll (millions)')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

win_pct_data['abs_win_pct_change'] = win_pct_data['win_pct'] - win_pct_data['prev_win_pct']
win_pct_data['win_pct_percent_gain'] = (win_pct_data['abs_win_pct_change'] / win_pct_data['prev_win_pct']) * 100

# Data for the top 5 improvements
teams_data = [
    {"team": "Arizona Diamondbacks", "year_from": 2010, "year_to": 2011, "win_pct_from": 0.401, "win_pct_to": 0.580, "improvement": 0.179, "percent": 17.9},
    {"team": "Boston Red Sox", "year_from": 2012, "year_to": 2013, "win_pct_from": 0.426, "win_pct_to": 0.599, "improvement": 0.173, "percent": 17.3},
    {"team": "Baltimore Orioles", "year_from": 2011, "year_to": 2012, "win_pct_from": 0.426, "win_pct_to": 0.574, "improvement": 0.148, "percent": 14.8},
    {"team": "Cleveland Indians", "year_from": 2012, "year_to": 2013, "win_pct_from": 0.420, "win_pct_to": 0.568, "improvement": 0.148, "percent": 14.8},
    {"team": "Oakland Athletics", "year_from": 2011, "year_to": 2012, "win_pct_from": 0.457, "win_pct_to": 0.580, "improvement": 0.123, "percent": 12.3}

# Create colors for each team
colors = ['#A71930', '#BD3039', '#DF4601', '#E31937', '#003831']  

# Create the plot
for i, team_data in enumerate(teams_data):
    # Plot the before and after points connected by a line
    years = [team_data['year_from'], team_data['year_to']]
    win_pcts = [team_data['win_pct_from'], team_data['win_pct_to']]

    plt.plot(years, win_pcts, 'o-', linewidth=4, markersize=10, 
             color=colors[i], label=team_data['team'], alpha=0.8)
    
    # Add improvement annotation
    mid_year = (team_data['year_from'] + team_data['year_to']) / 2
    mid_win_pct = (team_data['win_pct_from'] + team_data['win_pct_to']) / 2

    plt.annotate(f"+{team_data['improvement']:.3f}\n(+{team_data['percent']:.1f}%)",

If we look at plots of percent change in payroll versus win percent and change in win percent across all the data, we see only slight trends. Trends appear stronger for absolute changes in payroll than for percent changes in payrol.

This could be explained by the fact that large increases in payroll may be due to bringing on a star player if the win percent is low, which could lead to a higher win percent...In other words a bad team could improve a lot with a big payroll increase, while a good team might not improve much with a comparable payroll increase. Think of the law of diminishing returns.

4.4 Comparison

First, we create models (linear regressions) for the data in aggregate due to the small number of data points (<20) per team. This was not organized by quantiles as was done in sample notebook.

(Model 1): We created a model to predict the change in win percentage, we see that payroll is a significant predictor although percent change in payroll is not. However, the effect size is larger for the percent change in payroll. The R^2 is very low, showing a weak model and poor fit.

(Model 2): If we create a linear model to predict win percent, we see that both payroll and change in payroll are significant. While payroll is more significant, change in payroll has a larger effect size suggesting greater practical importance. This model has a much larger R^2 value compared to that of model (1% vs 13%).

Looking at a previous graph controlling for team (4.3), we see that we must consider Simpson's Paradox where aggregated data trends may not hold true at separate team levels.

(Model 3): We decided to model win percent rather than change in win percent, because we wanted to measure performance on an absolute basis. If a team wins at a 20% clip and then improves to 40% the next year, they would show massive improvement in win percent. However, they still perform terribly. A team that consistently wins at a 60% is performing excellently in a baseball context.

We decided to include both payroll and diff_payroll as predictors, because they are somewhat correlated and a multivariate regression controls for each predictor to give more accurate estimates of the coefficients. Using this model, we see that both payroll and change in payroll are significant predictors of win percent, and some team effects are significant. We also include an interaction term, since we saw in the graph that the slope varies by team.

The model has a fairly high R^2 of 0.35, so the team, payroll, and change in payroll explain about a third of the variation in win percent. This more complicated model is better than the simpler models that do not control for team effects. More variance in the data is explained, however, there remains a lot of unexplained variance, suggesting that other factors beyond payroll and team influence win percentage.
